<HEADLINE> British PM Blair Welcomes New IRA Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
welcomed here today the Irish Republican Army's (IRA) new
ceasefire, saying it would build a "new mood of hope for peace and
a lasting political settlement in Northern Ireland".
</P>
<P>
The IRA guerillas, fighting to end British rule in Northern
Ireland, announced this morning that it would implement an
"unequivocal" ceasefire from noon on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Blair said in a statement issued this afternoon: "I welcome
today's announcement which is good for the people of Northern
Ireland and for the people of Britain."
</P>
<P>
"Following the continuing loyalist ceasefire and the courageous
Orange Order decisions (cancelling planned marches) last week,
this can build on a new mood of hope for peace and a lasting
political settlement in Northern Ireland," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair also made it clear that the British government wanted to
see whether the new IRA truce was genuine before Sinn Fein, the
political wing of IRA, could be allowed to attend the all-party
peace talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we will want to assess the ceasefire with great
care. What we and others want to see is an end to violence for
good and an irrevocable commitment to peaceful means," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
