<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flour Smuggling Reduces Zambians' Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of jobs in the milling
industry of Zambia are being wiped out yearly through flour
smuggling, the government has been told.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's Daily Mail today quoted National Milling Company
managing director Dawie Fourie as complaining that businessmen
from South Africa and Zimbabwe are trafficking huge quantities of
flour into Zambia without paying tax as they claim that the goods
are destined for the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot smuggling going on through the Chirundu
border. Traders from the south bring in a lot of subsidized flour
and evade tax by cheating that they were taking it to Congo,+ he
told Labor Minister Peter Machungwa recently.
</P>
<P>
He said the newly privatized National Milling Company has the
capacity to buy over 90 percent of the wheat grown in Zambia but
its ability is hampered by competition from the cheaper products
from outside the country.
</P>
<P>
His company has put its own workers at Chirundu in southeast
Zambia to see how many truck loads of flour get through and they
have found that huge quantities come in without duty and in the
process get off loaded in Zambia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The director suggested that all traders should be made to pay
deposit customs duty at Chirundu and when they reach another
border post to enter Zaire, they should be refunded to ensure
that there is no cheating.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa assured him that his ministry will move to secure
jobs for Zambians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
