<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Ends Peace Talks with Tribal Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the Bangladeshi
government and tribal rebels, which began on Monday, ended today
without formulating a draft peace agreement to end the
long-standing insurgency in the southern Chittagong Hill Tracts
(CHT).
</P>
<P>
However, Chief Whip Hasnat Abdullah, who led the government
delegation, told reporters that "the on-going process to prepare a
draft treaty is satisfactory."
</P>
<P>
Tribal leader Shantu Larma, chairman of the Parbatya Chattagram
Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), said he does not want to say
anything at this stage.
</P>
<P>
It was the fifth round of talks under the present government.
Both sides announced during the last round of talks in May that
they would sign a peace treaty soon.
</P>
<P>
But the peace process received a severe jolt when differences
of opinion surfaced among the top leadership of the PCJSS, which
has struggled for about two decades for self-rule in the
resources-rich CHT.
</P>
<P>
During the just-ended talks, according to informed sources, the
PCJSS were pressing hard for total authority, instead of partial
authority as had been proposed earlier.
</P>
<P>
The sources said both sides were also yet to resolve their
differences on some other key issues, including the involvement of
the United Nations in the repatriation of the tribal refugees in
Tripura of India.
</P>
<P>
The schedule of the next rounds of talks would be fixed with
the consent of the two sides through a liaison committee, the
sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
