<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Hold Talks on Water Sharing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indo-Bangladesh Joint Rivers
Commission (JRC) today held here its first ministerial-level
meeting in seven years and discussed a number of issues, said
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak held talks
with his Indian counterpart Sis Ram Ola on the implementation of
the accord to share the water of the Ganges and on a number of
other issues including the sharing of the water of the river
Teesta.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we discussed many issues since a lot of matters have
been accumulated over the last seven years," Water Resources
Secretary Shamsul Hud told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He claimed "considerable progress" has been made in the talks.
"The talks have begun on a cordial note," he added.
</P>
<P>
The two-day JRC meeting is the outcome of the summit meeting on
January this year between former Indian prime minister Deve Gowda
and his Bangladesh counterpart Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers signed the 30-year Ganges water treaty
in New Delhi on December 11 last year, agreeing to share the
Ganges water in dry season.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was the 32nd JRC meeting since the formation of
the commission in 1972. The last JRC meeting was held in Dhaka in
June 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
