<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, India Conclude Talks on Border Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the
Nepal-India Joint Working Group on border management concluded
here today with consensus on some issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the existing mechanisms of management
along their 1750-kilometre open border, and agreed to improve the
management, said a press release of the Nepali Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The joint working group, set up last year by the two
governments to control undesirable activities through cross-border
movements, identified such trans-border problems as movement of
criminals and other undesirable elements and illicit movement of
goods.
</P>
<P>
The two sides raised suggestions for improving border
management and enhancing cooperation in discouraging movement of
undesirable elements and goods across the border, and for
strengthening cooperation in combating crime and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Nepal raised the issue of a poor communication link with the
border areas during the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The working group agreed to improve channels of communication,
including those between the security agencies and district
authorities of the two countries, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
As agreed by the two sides, the working group will meet
alternatively in Kathmandu and New Delhi at least once every six
months.
</P>
<P>
It may constitute sub-groups to discuss specific issues, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting of the joint working group will be held in
New Delhi in October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
