<HEADLINE> Liberian Election Going On Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Liberians throughout the country
went out to vote today for a president after seven years of civil
war that claimed the life of more than 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
In the capital Monrovia, voters were seen in long queues
waiting peacefully for their turn to choose among 13 presidential
candidates, according to a television broadcast here.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers of the west peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG and
electoral personnel were shown keeping watch at every ballot box
to ensure no mistake or malpractice would occur.
</P>
<P>
International observers, including former U.S. President Jimmy
Carter, were also at polling stations to monitor the voting
process.
</P>
<P>
The two most hopeful presidential candidates, former warlord
Charle Taylor of the National Patriotic Party and Ellen
Johnson-Sirleaf of Unity Party, the only female aspirant, were
also seen casting their own votes.
</P>
<P>
Both Liberia's Independent Electoral Commission and ECOMOG
have repeatedly promised what was going on would be a free and
fair election.
</P>
<P>
It is reported the voting process, which began this morning,
is still going on smoothly. And Monrovia, the once battlefield of
warring factions, is quiet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
