<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hussein, Mubarak Keen to Break Peace Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- King of Jordan Hussein and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak are keen to put the stalled Middle East
peace process back on track, a senior Jordanian official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir
Mutawe made the remarks during a regular press conference, in
response to questions about the summit between the two leaders
in the near future, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders were always exchanging visits and consulting
each other on the peace process, Mutawe said.
</P>
<P>
He did not give further details about the upcoming summit
between Hussein and Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt have been trying to overcome the obstacles
facing the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks and this was part of
the Arab efforts to help the Palestinians regain their
legitimate rights on their national soil, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mutawe disclosed that Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul Salam Majali will meet Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
Sunday in the West Bank to boost coordination in the peace
efforts and review ways to break the current impasse.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are also expected to sign a health agreement, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan mediated the Hebron accord between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority in January this year, which
was considered a major breakthrough in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, later in March, Israel declared to build the Jewish
settlement at Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem, thus stalling the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
From March till now, efforts by the United States and Egypt to
reactivate the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks failed due to
Israeli government's hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt are the only two countries in the Arab world
that have signed peace treaties with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
