<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storms Strike Illinois, Wisconsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Strong thunderstorms and
possible tornadoes lashed northern Illinois and southern Wisconsin
Friday night, knocking down trees, tearing off roofs and leaving
150,000 homes without electricity.
</P>
<P>
A 46-year man, Ramon Soto, was struck by lightning in the
storms with winds of up to 70 miles per hour on Chicago's
Northwest Side, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
In Chicago suburb, one of the hardest hit areas, large areas
were darkened as the rush-hour storms came through. Winfield,
Illinois, suffered the most damage as all the 20 businesses in the
Prairie Trail Center shopping center were damaged with broken
windows, ripped facades and uprooted trees as a result of heavy
winds and golf ball-sized hail.
</P>
<P>
In Mokena, Illinois, 70 mile-per-hour winds picked up a
semi-trailer truck on westbound Interstate 80 and threw it over a
cement divider into oncoming traffic, an Associated Press report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
