<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Pledges to Work for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides has reiterated his government's desire for a solution
to the Cyprus problem the soonest possible.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the people of Cyprus, broadcasted this
evening, on the occasion of the coup staged by the Greek
military junta on July 15, 1974 and the Turkish invasion that
followed five days later, Clerides described these "tragic
events" as "the darkest periods of Cyprus' history."
</P>
<P>
He said that one of the conclusions of these tragic events
concerns the relations between the Greek and Turkish
communities in the island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed that the two communities must envisage and
plan a common future, noting that "as we enter the 21st century,
we must abandon the mentality and practices which have brought
about so many ills to Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He said a fair solution must be found, which will heal the
wound of the past and establish a climate of confidence, mutual
understanding and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that the Greek Cypriot side has shown
"goodwill and made painful concessions" during the past 23
years.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government also showed a positive attitude during
the U.N.-led direct negotiations between himself and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, held in the U.S. on July 9-12, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed that his government will show the same
attitude in the second round of negotiations, scheduled to be
held in Switzerland on August 11-16, saying that "our ferment
desire is to achieve a solution to the Cyprus problem the
soonest possible."
</P>
<P>
"We all hope that the process that has already started may be
the starting point of an unprecedented effort to find a
solution," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the government policy that has attracted
international involvement in the Cyprus issue has increased hopes
for finding a solution.
</P>
<P>
Clerides assured that he will devote all his energy "to
ensure that this course may have the desirable conclusion to the
benefit of the two communities."
</P>
<P>
However, He stressed that he will not accept a solution "that
will not safeguard the future of Greek Cypriots, whatever the
price we may have to pay for our stand."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since the island was
divided following the Turkish invasion in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite this
Mediterranean island nation as a bi-communal, bi-zonal federation
through peace talks, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
