<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and the European Investment Bank today signed
an agreement to organize future relations through the Bank's
Mediterranean Aid Program, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Minister of State for Planning and
International Cooperation Zafer Al-Beshri and the bank's deputy
chairman.
</P>
<P>
A financing contract was also signed within the framework of
the agreement between the bank and the National Bank of Egypt, by
which the European bank offers a 75 million ECUs to EgyptAir to
contribute to financing the purchase of two Airbus planes.
</P>
<P>
The agreement falls within the context of promoting relations
between Egypt and the European Union and channeling conventional
cooperation between them into partnership, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the European Investment Bank, one of the European
Union's institutions, have enjoyed close relations of cooperation
for 20 years now that led to the bank's contribution to
developing the Egyptian economy and the infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Pedco Metal Industries, an Israeli defense
company, has announced it has been awarded a contract by
U.S. aviation giant McDonnell-Douglas to manufacture and supply
structural fittings for the GPS system fitted on F-15 combat
aircraft, reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The order for the fittings was sent to Pedco president and
owner, Joe Ray, by MacDonnell-Douglas vice president, Joe
Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
Pedco is an internationally known supplier of metal product
to aerospace organizations in Israel and throughout the
world. The current contract forms part of McDonnell-Douglas's 2
billion U.S. dollar reciprocal procurement program in Israel.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel Electric Corporation (IEC) and
Ministry of National Infrastructure are ready to invite tenders
for the construction of the country's largest private power
station, reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The new facility is due to have a power of 370 megawatts and
will cost between 300-400 million U.S. dollars. It will produce
electric power from natural gas.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign companies are expected to make a bid for
the forthcoming IEC tender. Among the leading names mentioned on
this regard are U.S.-based energy giant Amoco, French energy
organization ABB and Ensaldo from Italy, in addition to several
companies from the Far East.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Robomatics, an Israeli high-tech company, has won
a contract, valued at approximately 5 million U.S. dollars, to
supply hard drive testing systems, reported bi-weekly Israel
Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The order was placed by a U.S.-based company and delivery is
scheduled for completion by November this year.
</P>
<P>
The systems are based on the proprietary "Black Horn"
technology developed by subsidiary company, DDAS. The system
allows users to trace minuscule defects on hard drive surfaces.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for Robomatics explained that the DDAS system
examines metal and final hard drive surfaces. 
</P>
