<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carter Calls for Immediate Withdrawal of ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- As Liberians turned out in droves
to vote in the war-ravaged country's landmark election today,
former U.S. President Jimmy Carter has called on the west
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) to leave the country shortly after
election.
</P>
<P>
According to Carter, the planned stay of ECOMOG in Liberia for
another six months after the installation of a new democratic
government in August may no longer be feasible, the News Agency
of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
After meeting ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu
in the capital Monrovia on Friday, Carter said, "prevailing
circumstances" had necessitated a review of the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
He planned to discuss it with General Sani Abacha, Nigeria's
head of state and current chairman of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS), which sent the peace-keepers to
Liberia in the heat of the country's factional fighting in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Malu, however, said that ECOMOG's stay might have to be
extended as it had not started training Liberian armed forces and
national police to which the task of consolidating ECOMOG'S gains
on security would be bequeathed.
</P>
<P>
This mission of ECOMOG is included in the revised Abuja peace
accord signed last August to put an end to Liberia's civil war
and bring in place an elected government at last.
</P>
<P>
"Even from that point alone, I don't think the issue of
leaving Liberia six months after a new government is put in place
would be there," Malu explained.
</P>
<P>
The force commander, who noted that the mission was a strain
on the finances of ECOWAS member countries, did not give reasons
why the training had not begun but assured it was a prerequisite
for ECOMOG leaving Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Malu disclosed that the officer corps would be trained in west
African countries with appropriate training institutions, citing
Nigeria and Ghana, while those trained in 1989 would be trained
as trainers together with ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure you that we are going to restructure the armed
forces and police to the level determined to be detribalized," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that ECOMOG intends to train an army of about
4,000 and a police force of about 5,000 to cope with challenges
of post-ECOMOG Liberia.
</P>
<P>
After about seven years of operations, ECOMOG has succeeded in
disarming and demobilizing Liberia's warring factions, ensuring
security and an environment favorable for today's presidential
and legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
The first results of the elections, which began early this
morning, are expected to come out tomorrow while final results
are expected by the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
Liberians, some of whom went to polling centers for voting in
the midnight, are reported queuing quietly in today's election
watched by ECOMOG and international monitors, including Carter.
</P>
<P>
Among the 13 presidential candidates, former warlord Charles
Taylor of the National Patriotic Party and Mrs. Ellen
Johnson-Sirleaf are seen as the most hopeful.
Liberians will also elect for a 90-member parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
