<HEADLINE> Malawian Cabinet to be Streamlined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian government announced
today that its ministries will be reduced to 22 from 26 as part
of its civil service reform, according to reports reaching here
this evening.
</P>
<P>
Secretary in the President's Office Alfred Upindi said in
Blantyre, the biggest city of Malawi, that the government has
approved a new structure of the administration.
</P>
<P>
Upindi said the restructuring exercise will continue with an
evaluation of every job in the civil service and is expected to
be completed by November next year.
</P>
<P>
The ministries to be axed are those of natural resources;
research and environmental affairs; youth, sports and culture as
well as economic planning and development.
</P>
<P>
The irrigation and water development ministries will be merged
to form the Water Ministry and the Relief and Rehabilitation
Ministry will be merged into the Office of President while the
housing, land and physical planning ministries will also be
merged. 
</P>
