<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes IRA Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today welcomed the decision of the Irish Republican Army (IRA) to
restore a cease-fire in the British province of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton said that on the basis of the
announcement his government will work with Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing, to reach a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the U.S. will "strongly support those who
take risks" for peace, praising the leadership of both Sinn Fein
and the pro- British loyalists who have sought to quell attacks on
the part of their respective armed militias.
</P>
<P>
"This declaration, which we expect to be implemented
unequivocally and permanently, can open the door to inclusive
negotiations to achieve a just and lasting settlement," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the IRA announced a new truce in its 28-year war
against British rule in Northern Ireland. It was to take effect at
midday on Sunday and allow its Sinn Fein spokesmen a seat at peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"This is a moment of great possibility," Clinton said. "The
United States will work closely with the two governments and the
political parties to build on this historic opportunity," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has put Northern Ireland high on his
diplomatic agenda and in December 1995 became the first American
president to visit the troubled province.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has been excluded from the peace talks on Northern
Ireland since the IRA suspended a ceasefire more than one year
ago. and the newly-offered truce will pave the way for the party
to participate the all-party talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
