<HEADLINE> Serb President Plavsic Expelled from Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic was expelled from the ruling Serb Democratic Party (SDS)
at the party's executive committee session at Saturday night, a
SDS communique, released today in Serb capital Pale, said.
</P>
<P>
The party also demanded Plavsic to step down from office and
transfer her authorities to Vice-President Dragoljub Mirjanic.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five of the 84 committee members attended the overnight
session and voted unanimously to expel Plavsic from the party and
release her from all her duties as a committee member.
</P>
<P>
The communique gave the reasons of Plavsic's expulsion, saying
that was because she "betrayed" the ruling party and the state
authorities, adopted some measures that "violated the Dayton Peace
Accord and the Serb constitution" and "defamed" leaders of the
party and the Serb entity.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic's expulsion is the latest outcome of the waging power
struggle within the SDS and the Republika Srpska (RS), which went
open on June 28 when President Plavsic dismissed the Interior
Minister Dragan Kijac in the name of inefficiency on crime
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
Her daring move triggered angers from the government, which
announced her decision "against the constitution".
</P>
<P>
On July 1, the ruling SDS held an executive committee meeting,
calling on the parliament to remove Plavsic from office. But two
days later, Plavsic dissolved the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The parliament responded on July 4 by announcing Plavsic's
decision "against the constitution" and threatened to dismiss her
from her post if she does not withdraw her decision.
</P>
<P>
As the struggle went fiercer, Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb
member of Bosnia's tripartite presidency, and Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic held talks with Plavsic and wanted to mediate
between the rival sides.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts to persuade Plavsic to take back her decision of
dissolving the parliament ended in vain as the tough lady
resolutely turned down their suggestions.
</P>
<P>
As Plavsic was elected president in September 1996 as the
candidate of the SDS, she is now very likely be removed from the
highest place of the RS if she ignores SDS's decision of expulsion
and insists not to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
