<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier on Economic Development of Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua,
addressing an economic symposium marking the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region today,
stressed the need for the country's ethnic-minority regions to
focus on economic development.
</P>
<P>
Zou, who is heading a central government delegation to attend
the region's anniversary celebrations here, said at the symposium
that Inner Mongolia should stick to the basic line of seizing
opportunities, deepening reforms, opening wider to the outside
world, promoting development and maintaining stability, so as to
push for overall economic and social progress.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years fundamental changes have occured in
Inner Mongolia's economy, society and people's life. Since the
implementation of the reform and open policy in 1979 particularly,
the region has witnessed its most rapid and best development
period, Zou said.
</P>
<P>
The annual economic growth rate has averaged 9.7 percent in the
past 18 years in the region, making it reach the target of
re-doubling its gross domestic product (GDP) of 1980 five years
ahead of schedule, the vice-premier said, calling this "marvelous
progress."
</P>
<P>
He attributed the success to the efforts of the region's people
of all ethnic groups, different levels of party committees and
governments, which have given top priority to developing the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Experience has shown that the modernization of ethnic-minority
regions cannot be separated from that of the country and the
nation as a whole, Zou noted.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic-minority regions should unswervingly adhere to economic
construction as the central task, and all efforts should serve
this center, he stressed. Quoting a theory of Deng Xiaoping, Zou
said that anything that benefits the development of productive
forces should be adhered to; otherwise, it ought to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
Also, the vice-premier urged Inner Mongolia to pay more
attention to the market in developing the local economy, and to
expand local advantages, intensify regional cooperation, promote
economic development with science and technology, and walk on a
road of sustainable development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
