<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik Government, Rebels Exchange POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Tajik government and the rebels
today exchanged another group of 97 prisoners of war and ended the
first round of exchange which started on Friday, said a report
from the Tajik capital of Dushambe.
</P>
<P>
The government released 48 POWs, and the rebels, in return,
sent back 49, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The exchange was carried out under the landmark peace accord
the Tajik government and the rebels signed in Moscow last month,
which ended the tiny central Asian country's four-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, a total of 100 POWs, 50 from each
side, should be released during the exchange on July 18-20.
</P>
<P>
Tajik government explained that three more POWs, two from the
government side and one from the rebels, would be released in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
A group of international observers supervised the
exchange. They praised the smooth exchange and said it not only
showed the two sides' determination to fully carry out their peace
agreement but also enhanced mutual confidence.
</P>
<P>
Another report said that the government and the rebels reached
agreement on the next round of POWs exchange.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts among different political, religious and ethnic
groups intensified in Tajikistan since the country gained
independence in September 1991 after the collapse of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
Islamic opposition forces, the main rival of the Tajik
government, set up bases in mountainous border areas between
Tajikistan and Afghanistan and launched a guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale fighting ended after the Tajik government and the
opposition forces signed a truce in December 1996, but sporadic
clashes continued until the two sides signed peace accord in
June. By then, the rebels held a total of 256 government
soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
