<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Cracks Down on Government Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced today that it is
setting up a special court to deal further with rampant
governmental corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Persian-language evening paper Kayhan reported that both
the parliament and judiciary have taken up measures to fight
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Judicial chief Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi said "Signing of
unfair contracts, issuance of fake permits and some illegal
privatization cases in factories and firms will be given high
priority in this court."
</P>
<P>
Yazdi's announcement came on the heels of the latest attacks
by the country's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei on government
officials who have become rich through illegal means.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow the formation of a class whose wealth is
accumulated through illegal ways," Khamenei stressed last week.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Iranian authorities concerned have launched a
new campaign against corruption, calling it a "dangerous
phenomenon" that must be confronted.
</P>
<P>
Iranian speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri said at the parliament
that what he termed an "opportunist class of the rich" causes
economic insecurity in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Nateq-Nouri suggested that an appropriate parliamentary
committee should work together to identify the corrupted rich
people whom he called "traitors."
</P>
<P>
On July 1, some 156 members of the 270-seat parliament called
for investigations into the assets of top officials of the
Rafsanjani administration and their families.
</P>
<P>
The latest anti-corruption campaign comes at the end of the
Rafsanjani's term of office. Outgoing Rafsanjani, who has been
president of the Islamic republic for two consecutive terms, will
officially step down on August 3.
</P>
<P>
Corruption became rampant towards the end of Iran's 1980-88
war with Iraq, becoming a significant economic factor in the
free-wheeling days of post-war reconstruction during Rafsanjani's
first term of office.
</P>
<P>
Public concern increased with the exposures two years ago of
scandals at banks and state agencies involving misuse of hundreds
of millions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In June, a court sentenced to death a man arrested seven
years ago for cheating investors.
</P>
<P>
A state official and 12 accomplices were also sentenced to up
to 30 years of imprisonment for appropriating large sums of
state money allocated for rebuilding earthquake-hit areas, and a
former Revolutionary Guards commander was put on trial for
treason and embezzlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
