<HEADLINE> Trial of Israeli Spy in Egypt Delayed Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Higher State Security
Court has decided to put off until next Saturday the trial of four
defendants charged of spying for Israel to undermine Egypt's
national and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
It is the fourth time that the hearings of the case have been
adjourned since they opened on April 24, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Azam Azam, a 35-year-old Israeli textile engineer, and his
Egyptian colleague, 34-year-old Emad Abdul Hamid Ismail, arrested
last November, had pleaded their innocence to charges of spying for
the Jewish state that can carry sentences of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
During Saturday's hearing, the Egyptian defense attorney
alleged that the real motive in the case was to stop the
normalization of Egyptian-Israeli relations, according to today's
Egyptian Gazette.
</P>
<P>
"Is there really an espionage case? The case is meant to stop
normalization," said Faird al-Dib, a distinguished lawyer, who was
punched by his Egyptian colleage after the court adjourned its
second hearing of the case on May 18.
</P>
<P>
The court will continue to listen to his pleading next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Dib has been harshly criticized for agreeing to defend the
alleged Israeli spy.
</P>
<P>
Zohra Yousef Giris and Mona Ahmed Shuwahna, two Israeli women,
also stood trial in absentia in previous hearings. They are
accused of recruiting the Egyptian for spying for Mossad, the
Israeli intelligence.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to have a peace treaty with
Israel but ties have been cool. The spy case, however, added to
the tensions because of the Mideast peace deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
