<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Results for Liberia's Election Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Due to bad weather and water
logged roads in the interior parts of Liberia, early results for
the country's presidential election are not expected until late
today.
</P>
<P>
After seven years of one of the bloodiest civil wars in the
African continent, over 700,000 Liberian voters trooped up 1,900
polling stations Saturday in the country's first democratic
election.
</P>
<P>
Journalists in Monrovia said hundreds of voters had lined up
to cast their ballot long before 7:00 am GMT when the polls
opened in the capital and other towns.
</P>
<P>
"Polling stations in outlying areas were opened an hour or two
later but the delay did not deter the excitement on the faces of
many voters who see the election as the way forward for Liberia",
one radio journalist said.
</P>
<P>
Liberia Radio reported that dozens of voters brough sandwiches
and other foodstuff as they lined up for the vote and at least
six stations in Monrovia ran out of ballot papers within three
hours of the opening of the polls.
</P>
<P>
Security remains tight with heavily-armed west African
peacekeeping (ECOMOG) troops patrolling the streets and watching
polling stations with binoculars from discreet distances.
</P>
<P>
Charles Taylor, one of the 13 presidential candidates, made a
sweeping tour of polling stations in Monrovia before flying to
Gbarngba, his one time factional stronghold to cast his vote.
</P>
<P>
"By the destiny of God, I shall be President Charles Taylor by
early next week," he boasted to reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Taylor's major rival Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf visited dozens of
polling booths and waved victory signs to mainly women
supporters."
</P>
<P>
"We shall see who would have the last laugh", she said in
response to Taylor's taunting during the campaign that the
election was not a woman's affair.
</P>
<P>
Election officials said some of the ballot boxes would have to
be brought to counting stations by dugout canoes and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
There are 13 presidential candidates contending in the
election which will also result in parliament members.
</P>
<P>
The Star, an independent radio station funded by the American
government will broadcast the election results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
