<HEADLINE> Philippine Defense Secretary Announces Bid for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary Renato
de Villa today formally announced his bid for the presidency in
the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
De villa, who joined President Fidel Ramos' Lakas-NUCD
(National Union of Christian Democrats) recently, is one of the
seven presidential contenders within the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
Other presidential hopefuls in the ruling party include Speaker
Jose de Venecia, Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo and President
Ramos' sister Senator Leticia Ramos-Shahani.
</P>
<P>
"I'll go straight to the point. I accept the challenge," de
Villa told a crowd of about 20,000 at the Lyceum University of
Batangas, Batangas Province, where he celebrated his 62nd
birthday.
</P>
<P>
De Villa said he had gone through six months of consultations
and capability assessment and found out a strong clamor for him to
run.
</P>
<P>
"Who can refuse? Who can turn his back to this public clamor?"
de Villa said.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, who became defense chief in July 1991, said his
vision is to push further the country's unity and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a presidential contender, he will present
himself as an alternative to the traditional politician.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to present the country with someone whose record of
service is not disturbed by dirt," he said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came two days after de Villa and other
presidential contenders from the ruling Lakas-NUCD had a meeting
with President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the presidential palace said the official
presidential candidate of Lakas-NUCD will be selected through a
series of consultative assemblies and will be announced by
President Ramos, chairman of the party, on or before the party's
national convention on November 27.  
</P>
