<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberian Election Ends Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited Liberian election
ended Saturday peacefully, with an exceptionally large turnout of
voters, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
In Monrovia, the capital city, voters filed out to the polling
stations as early as 7:00 a.m., defying the early morning rain.
</P>
<P>
The voting went on peacefully and orderly in the polling
stations, all of which were manned by soldiers of west African
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
It ended peacefully at 4:00 p.m.. No violence was reported
during the election.
</P>
<P>
Altogether there were some 11,000 ECOMOG soldiers deployed
nationwide to provide security for the election.
</P>
<P>
The election was supervised by over 500 observers from the
United Nations, the European Union and other international
organizations. Noteworthy among them is former U.S. President
Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
Former warlord and presidential candidate of the National
Patriotic Party Charles Taylor reportedly cast his vote in his
home in Monrovia suburb. He is widely regarded as most likely
winner of the election.
</P>
<P>
Two other former warlords, George Boley of the National
Democratic Party of Liberia and Alhaji Kromah of the All Liberian
Coalition Party, also took part in the election.
</P>
<P>
Among the 13 presidential candidates from 13 political
parties, Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, a former senior official of the
United Nations and the only female aspirant, is regarded as the
most likely rival of Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Of the over 2.6 million population in Liberia, 710,000 were
registered as voters.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election is expected to lead Liberia to final peace
after seven years of civil war that has killed more than 150,000
people and made many more others homeless.
</P>
<P>
However, no matter who will be announced the winner next week,
he or she will face the challenge of persuading the losers to
accept the results, and this is what the international community
is concerned at the moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
