<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Central Government Support for Inner Mongolia, Zou Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua
said today that the central government will give more support for
the development of north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Zou, who is also a member of the Political Bureau of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), told a
gala ceremony in this capital of Inner Mongolia, marking the 50th
anniversary of the foundation of the region, that there will be no
change in the central government's support for Inner Mongolia, as
the comprehensive national strength and revenue are increasing.
</P>
<P>
He said that the founding of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region was an example of the successful policy of the CPC for
solving ethnic problems, and a model of New China in implementing
autonomy for ethnic regions.
</P>
<P>
The achievements of the region over the past 50 years have been
superior to those of any other historical period, said Zou, who is
heading a central government delegation. This demonstrates that,
in order to maintain the region's stability and speed up its
development, efforts must be made to uphold Marxism, Mao Zedong
Thought and Deng Xiaoping's Theory of Building Socialism with
Chinese Characteristics, to adhere to the leadership of the
Chinese Communist Party and the road of socialism, stick to the
system of autonomy for ethnic regions, and focus on economic
development, he added.
</P>
<P>
The region has sound development opportunities and will have a
bright future, as it is rich in natural resources. It also has a
good basis after half a century's development, as the state has
been attaching great importance to the development of ethnic
regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zou pointed out that the top priority is to develop the local
economy and raise the living standards of the local people.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that different levels of government of the region
strengthen the basic role of agriculture, and expand the
processing of agricultural, animal, and forestry products, as well
as the pillar industries of energy and metallurgy.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia should open wider to the outside world as a way
of promoting development, and push ahead with reforms in different
spheres with flexible policies and measures, though in a positive
and steady manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier also emphasized the need to strengthen unity
of all ethnic groups, maintain social stability and safeguard
national unity, calling these "the fundamental prerequisites" for
Inner Mongolia's progress.
</P>
<P>
The Party Central Committee and the State Council fully affirms
the region's successful efforts in the past five decades to ensure
unity of all ethnic groups, social stability and sound border
defense, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he asked people and officials in the region to watch
against infiltration attempts made by Western hostile forces at
the country's ethnic regions by using ethnic and religious issues.
</P>
<P>
While all officials and people in general need to fight firmly
against hostile attempts at sabotaging ethnic and national unity,
and social stability, efforts must be made to properly handle
different kinds of social contraditions that run counter to unity
and stability, thus ensuring a sound social environment for reform,
opening, and economic construction, and safeguarding the unity and
lasting stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, work on law building should be accelerated,
he said, adding that ethnic regional autonomy should be improved
with efforts to make it more suited to the system of the socialist
market economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
