<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tortuous but Bright Road Before Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 20 (Xinhua) -- As the first female pilot in
Lebanon's Middle East Airlines and probably also in the Arab
world, Rola Hoteit has become acceptable among her colleges,
but not by all people in a society where women are still
struggling to prove their values.
</P>
<P>
As a woman entering such a profession, the 23-year-old Hoteit
has come across a few cases of gender discrimination from
passengers.
</P>
<P>
"One day, as an airplane is about to take off from the Beirut
Airport, a passenger heard that there was a woman pilot on board
and went completely insane. He got up and started shouting,
demanding that the plane be stopped because he didn't want to
die," Hoteit told the story in a weekend party of university
mates.
</P>
<P>
"He said that a woman cannot possibly be capable of flying a
plane and that if I was trying to learn flying at that
particular time, he would rather I learn during flights when
he's not on board," she said.
</P>
<P>
"After pushing and shoving with the crew to open the door and
failed, he sat down, practically shivering during the entire
flight," the vivacious Hoteit chuckled.
</P>
<P>
She said, however, that she has never felt regret for the
decision to be a pilot. "Women are able to take on the
same jobs as men and they must not think that their only job is
to bear children and tidy the house," she added.
</P>
<P>
"Becoming a pilot was not a childhood dream, but rather
something I decided during my third year at the American
University of Beirut where I was majoring in Mathematics,"
Hoteit explained.
</P>
<P>
The decision came about almost by accident. "A friend of mine
came up to me one day holding a newspaper in his hand, laughing
quite loudly and arrogantly. When I asked him what it was so
funny, he said that the MEA was asking for pilots in an
advertisement, and what was making him laugh so much was that
they were also asking for female pilots."
</P>
<P>
"I was so furious at his insulting attitude that I decided to
challenge him. Why don't we both apply, I said, and we'll see
who succeeds. He never made it."
</P>
<P>
Hoteit quickly developed a fascination with becoming a
pilot. But she still had two main obstacles: her father and the
exams she needed to pass.
</P>
<P>
"My father said I could go through the exams just to prove I
could do it, but I could not dream of ever pursuing a career
as a pilot," she recalled. "Without his permission, the road
ahead looked arduous."
</P>
<P>
With her perseverance and mathematical mind, Hoteit breezed
through her exams, ranking third out of the ten people accepted.
</P>
<P>
"After passing my exams, I had one week to prepare to go to
Scotland for 13 months of intensive flight training and studies
at the Air Service Training School," Hoteit said.
</P>
<P>
"I still had to convince my father so I decided to withdraw
from my university courses at the beginning of the
semester. Finally, he gave me his blessing."
</P>
<P>
With only one other woman from Africa and 500 men at the
school, Hoteit began her career as a pilot.
</P>
<P>
Homesick at the beginning, she nevertheless found her first
flying experience on a one-engine plane the most exciting moment
of her life.
</P>
<P>
"I started out my training in a one-engine propeller
aircraft, fitting two people, where I had to fulfill 50 hours -
15 hours with my instructor and 35 hours solo," Hoteit said. She
later moved onto a two-engine jet plane.
</P>
<P>
Two-and-a-half years later, Hoteit today flies airplanes like
Boeing 707 and Airbus 320.
</P>
<P>
As a first officer, she has completed 800 flights hours and
still needs to fly 3,200 hours more to gain the four stripes of
a captain. 
</P>
