<HEADLINE> Qatar Remains Determined to Host Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Qatar remains determined to
convene the fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic
Conference that may include Israeli delegates despite boycott
threats, the Qatari news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to live up to our international obligations
with regard to convening the economic conference in Doha," Qatari
Emir Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa al Thani told the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Qatar is due to host the conference in November, but
Syria has been leading calls to boycott the meeting in
response to Israel's hardline settlement policies that have
brought the Middle East peace process to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
Israel attended the three previous gatherings in Morocco,
Jordan and Egypt that were aimed at boosting economic
integration in the region while Syria boycotted the previous
three because of Israel's participation.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has repeatedly said it plans to go ahead with the
meeting and it expected Israel's participation because the meeting
is a " purely economic forum."
</P>
<P>
The Qatari Emir denied reports that other Arab states will
boycott the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I have not received officially any reply not to attend.
Each state has the right to practice the policy it wants,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On Qatar's determination to hold the conference, Syrian
official daily Al Thawara said Saturday, "We are astonished by
Qatar's attitude which is insisting on holding the conference for
what it claims the good of the Arabs. Holding such a conference
will allow Israel to divide the Arabs and to better dominate
them." 
</P>
