<HEADLINE> Teenage Wins 125cc Race at German Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian teenage Valentino Rossi held
off the challenge from Japanese Yoshiaki Katoh to win the 125cc
race, his seventh in nine this season, at the German Grand Prix
Sunday at Nurburgring.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Rossi steered his Aprilia through 23 laps -- a
total of 104.46km -- in 48:05.749 to increase his world
championship lead.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Katoh was second on his Yamaha, just over half-a-second
behind Rossi. German Manfred Geissler was third on his
Aprilia. Both men recorded career-best results.
</P>
<P>
World championship third-placed Tomomi Manako of Japan took the
early lead until he crashed his Honda on lap three. His
second-placed compatriot Noboru Ueda slid out on his Honda at the
same corner a couple of laps later.
</P>
<P>
Kazuto Sakata of Japan led the race on his Aprilia until he was
forced to pull out with mechanical problems after 15 laps --
leaving the way clear for Rossi.
</P>
<P>
Rossi now has 195 points after his fourth straight win. Ueda is
second on 123, Manako third on 111 and Sakata fourth on 101.
</P>
<P>
Later on Sunday, Tetsuya Harada of Japan, riding an Aprilia,
claimed the 250cc race by clocking 42min 36.307sec for the
113.75km.
</P>
<P>
Harada finished the line just ahead of Olivier Jacque of
France, Ralf Waldmann of Germany and three-time world champion Max
Biaggi of Italy, all on Hondas.
</P>
<P>
The four riders swapped the lead throughout the race, setting
up a finish in which all crossed the line within the space of
13-100ths of a second.
</P>
<P>
Biaggi now holds a lead of only two points in the
championship. He has 149 points to 147 for Waldmann and 142 for
the improving Harada. Jacque is fourth on 101. 
</P>
</TEXT>
