<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Exports to Africa Doubled: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's annual
exports to Africa doubled from 1.9 billion U.S. Dollars in 1994
to 3.8 billion Dollars in 1996, according to a survey by the
South African Institute of Race Relations.
</P>
<P>
The trade balance is heavily weighted in South Africa's favor,
although its imports from Africa recorded at 733 million Dollars
in 1996, up 41 percent from 1994.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's trade with the Southern African Customs Union
(Namibia, Lesotho, Swaziland and Botswana) took the lead,
followed by Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's trade with other African countries is expected
to continue to grow and could account for up to 25 percent of
exports within about 10 years, local economist Erika Prinsloo
said.
</P>
<P>
She cited Mozambique and Angola as immediate targets for South
African exports and investment because both had to recover from
severe devastation caused by civil war. 
</P>
