<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Passes Law on Women's Alimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian Parliament today
approved a special bill to allow women to receive their alimony
based on inflation growth over the years.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio reported that the new bill would
make it mandatory for marriage license bureaus to register the
price indicators in the marriage certificate at the time of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
The price indicator is provided by the Central Bank of
Iran, according to the report. Most of married women are
housewives in the country and their living largely depends on
their husbands.
</P>
<P>
Under Islamic law implemented in Iran, a wife can claim her
alimony both during her marriage or at the time of divorce. The
husband pledges the amount at the time marriage contract is
signed. He will have to pay the alimony any time his wife demands
it.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, men have preferred to designate their alimony
in money terms because they realized the monetary unit rial is
devaluating. Whereas women prefer to dozens or hundreds of gold
coins rather than rials.
</P>
<P>
The law applies to alimony that has been allocated in the
country's depreciating currency rial. Rial has been rapidly
devalued over the past 18 years since the Islamic revolution as a
result of drastic drop of the oil export revenue and runaway
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani told the Persian
daily Jomhuri Islami Saturday that the total inflation since 1989
stood at 595 percent. Non-official estimates have put annual
inflation in Iran as high as 30-60 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Vahideh Dastjerdi, a woman MP who supported the passage of
the bill, said that over the years, the alimony has been
depreciated to the point that it is not worth claiming by
women who are getting divorced.
</P>
<P>
The alimony of many women who were married decades ago is
not even enough to pay for her cab fare to the court to
get her divorce, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Bangladesh Water Talks End with Positive Outcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Indo-Bangladesh Joint Rivers
Commission (JRC) ended its two-day meeting here today and both
sides expressed optimism about the solution of problems regarding
the water sharing issue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of Water Resources Sis Ram Ola told a press
conference today that his government would do everything for the
implementation of the Ganges water sharing treaty, signed last
December.
</P>
<P>
"We will implement every word of the treaty and it is being
implemented," said the visiting Indian minister.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak expressed his
satisfaction at the outcome of the talks, saying: "We have agreed
to resolve the water sharing problems in the interests of the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
Besides India's renewed assurances to implement the Ganges
Water Treaty, Razzak said, the meeting also came out with the
initiation of discussion on the water sharing of other common
rivers including Teesta.
</P>
<P>
Another important outcome was India's support for Bangladesh's
proposal to build a Ganges barrage, Razzak added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the two ministers signed the agreed minutes
of the just-concluded JRC meeting, which took place after a gap of
seven years.
</P>
<P>
The two sides in a joint communique agreed to revive the
Standing Committee and Local Level committees to resolve the
issues of tying of embankments, and sharing water of Teesta and
other common rivers.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to remove the bottlenecks in
implementation of the Ganges Treaty with further negotiations and
maintain transparency in the treaty's implementation both at
Farakka and at Hardinge Bridge.
</P>
<P>
The JRC meeting was the outcome of a summit meeting in January
between former Indian Premier Deve Gowda and his Bangladeshi
counterpart Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers signed the 30-year Ganges water treaty
in New Delhi on December 11 last year, agreeing to share the
Ganges water flow in dry season.
</P>
<P>
Today's JRC meeting was the 32nd since the formation of the
commission in 1972. Its next meeting will be held in New Delhi in
November.  
</P>
</TEXT>
