<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Launches First Self-made Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has fired its
first domestically made surface-to-surface missile in a test,
official Saudi Press Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Second Deputy Prime Minister and Defense and Aviation
Minister Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz was quoted as saying that
the missile which has a range of 35 to 60 kilometers was launched
at a new military firing range in the south of the Kingdom on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement during the inauguration of an
ammunition maintenance center in Al-Kharj, 100 kilometers
southeast of Saudi capital of Riyadh which was opened with the aim
of giving Saudi Arabia the ability to check and maintain its own
ammunition instead of sending it to foreign countries. It also
includes a firing range, from which the missile was fired.
</P>
<P>
He said "it is no secret that the kingdom possesses long-range
surface-to-surface missiles," without giving more details about
the test.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia intends to turn the naval base in Al-Kharj into a
military town with an advanced military school within four to five
years.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has an ambitious armament program and major arms
contract with Britain, the United States and France.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Press Agency quoted Mohammed Al-Hudaithy, the
general administrative manager of armament as saying Friday that
the launch comes within the framework of a program to check and
maintain ammunition and field experiments.
</P>
<P>
He said with the launch of the surface-to-surface missile,
work will start in the test track in Al-Kharj.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the project of the maintenance and field
experiment took four years to establish. It is considered one of
the most advanced technical projects to serve different sectors of
Saudi military forces. 
</P>
