<HEADLINE> China to Become Intel's 3rd Largest Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The vice-president of the Intel
Corporation of the US said here today that China will be Intel's
third-largest market in the world after the US and Japan within a few
years.
</P>
<P>
James W. Jarrett, also president of Intel's China region, said
that with a growing demand for computers across the country, China
has become the company's fastest-growing marketplace.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China's demand for personal computers
(PCs) has been increasing at an average annual rate of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Intel's sales in the second quarter of this year came to six
billion US dollars-worth, of which 1.2 billion dollars-worth was
in the Asia-Pacific region, where China is the major marketplace.
</P>
<P>
Jarrett said that he believed that although China ranks the
sixth in the company's world market currently, it is sure to rise
to third in a few years' time and eventually replace Japan as the
world's second-largest PC market. "Intel will do its best to
develop this market," he added.
</P>
<P>
Intel is building a large-scale factory in Shanghai's Pudong
New Area to produce computer components and parts. The investment
in the project's first phase is set at nearly 100 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company is working in cooperation with a number
of Chinese computer manufacturers in designing computers and
developing software suitable for use in China.
</P>
<P>
Intel plans to increase the number of its sales centers in
China to 11 from four at present, in a bid to spread its products
all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company will set up a purchasing center in China
soon, sources said. The center is expected to buy 160 million US
dollars-worth of computer and printer parts from Chinese factories
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
