<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Artist Holds Exhibition in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of visitors were
deeply touched here today by a fine art exhibition of a young
Chinese oil painter, Li Zijian, in a university art gallery.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, in Harriet and Charles Luckman Fine Arts and
Complex, California State University, presents Li's series of
paintings of mother and daughter, red quilt, the homeland, the
homeless and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Li's works, Dr. Patricia Woodlin, curator of the
exhibition and director of the gallery, said that the artist
"portrays people, Chinese or Americans, in such a way that they
are real people with love, dignity and dreams."
</P>
<P>
It is the 18th exhibition in an international tour since 1993,
when Li Zijian began to show his 100 oil paintings around the world.
</P>
<P>
U.N. secretary general Kofi Annan, after visiting a similar
exhibition in the U.N. headquarters last June, praised the
painter's commitment to world peace.
</P>
<P>
"You are a very fine artist, and your commitment to world peace
evidenced in your World Tour with the theme of "Humanity and Love"
is a tribute to your art and to your country." Annan wrote to him
recently.
</P>
<P>
Li said he will bring the exhibition to his motherland in 2000,
following the world tour to Canada, Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea,
Russia and East European countries during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Li was born in Hunan, China in 1954. In his childhood, he was
suffering from hardship because of his declining family. Yet the
warmth of his loving mother, the deep affection of his elder
sisters and neighbors are always in his memory. All these had
naturally contributed to his works. 
</P>
</TEXT>
