<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Starts Campaign To Sell Greenhouse Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Senior Australian officials will
travel around the world in a final bid to sell Australia's stance
on greenhouse gas emission reduction targets ahead of December's
Climate Change Convention Conference in Kyoto, Prime Minister John
Howard said today.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the hand-picked task force would try to persuade
American, Japanese and British government advisers to set
different targets for different countries.
</P>
<P>
Howard has failed to win support from the United States and
Japan during his talks with leaders of the two countries earlier
this year over greenhouse gas emission reduction targets proposed
by the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The EU wants all developed countries to reduce their emissions
by 15 percent of their 1990 output by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Australia argues that as the world's leading coal exporters,
dependent on greenhouse gas-producing fossil fuels, it stands to
lose more than other countries.
</P>
<P>
"In the government's view, there is still time before the Kyoto
meeting to develop a realistic and fair outcome based on
differentiation that would have a better chance of being
implemented than the options being proposed, in particular by the
European Union," Howard said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The task force, led by Environment Department Secretary Roger
Beale and Australia's Ambassador for the Environment, Howard
Bamsey, will meet senior officials in Washington, Tokyo and
London.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the task force will set out the steps
Australia is already taking to help limit its greenhouse gas
emissions and underline Australia's commitment to pulling its
weight in responding to climate change.
</P>
<P>
Howard warned last month that Australia will refuse to sign the
international agreement on greenhouse gas emission reduction
targets if it fails to obtain accommodation.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to be part of an agreement that damages
Australia," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
