<HEADLINE> S. African Arms Giant Makes Secret Deal with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The South African
state-owned arms manufacturer Denel is trying to make a
1.6-billion U.S. Dollars arms deal with a Middle East country,
local daily "The Sunday Independence" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed weapons export deal, including mobile artillery
and anti-aircraft missiles, would be the biggest of its kind in
South African history, informed sources were quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the deal would be finalized in
September, but declined to reveal the name of the client, saying
the deal would be torpedoed if the name was published.
</P>
<P>
Denel claimed that up to 30,000 jobs could be lost and the
companies itself could even be destroyed if the deal fell
through.
</P>
<P>
The industrial analysts said an export order of this magnitude
will revive the flagging fortunes of the South African arms
industry, which has been under pressure following military budget
cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been aggressively marketing its wares in the
Middle East and surrounding areas, with the exception of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Denel has signed a few deals with countries like Jordan, but a
signed deal with Turkey was reversed by South Africa's Arms
Control Committee because of disputes over Turkey's human rights
problems.
</P>
<P>
Last year a 667-million U.S. Dollar deal to sell tank-firing
systems to Syria was also reversed after unprecedented
international pressure led by the United States, which claimed
the arms deal would upset the military balance in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
