<HEADLINE> ASEAN Secretary-General's Post to Be Decided at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 20 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN might elect a new
secretary-general at its foreign ministers' meeting scheduled here
on July 24-25.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's current secretary-general Ajit Singh from Malaysia,
whose first term will be completed later this year, is seeking for
re-election, and at the same time, a candidate from the
Philippines is bidding for the secretary-general's post, according
to official sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers will decide whether to extend the term of
the current secretary-general or elect a new chief administrator,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers will decide and make a decision on a
candidate who will take over on January 1 next year, the Malaysian
national news agency reported, quoting an ASEAN official who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of ASEAN which groups Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, at
their two-day 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM), are expected
to discuss the appointment of the secretary-general during a
luncheon to be hosted by host Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi here on July 22, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new organizational structure of ASEAN, the post of
secretary-general would no longer be rotated among member
countries but would instead be elected "based on merit" for a
five-year term, and the elected can be re-elected for another
term.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general will be assisted by two deputy
secretaries-general instead of one as decided by the foreign
ministers during their special meeting here on May 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
