<HEADLINE> Nepal's Foreign Trade Up 23 Percent in 1st 9 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's total foreign trade
during the first nine months of the fiscal year 1996-97 stood at
about 86 billion rupees (1.5 billion U.S. dollars), up 23.7
percent over the same period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
During this period, Nepal's trade with its main partner India
increased by 7.7 percent at about 23.6 billion rupees (410 million
dollars), while trade with other countries stood at 62.4 billion
rupees (1.1 billion dollars), up 31 percent, according to the
latest Economic Survey for Fiscal Year 1996-97 ending on July 14.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 16.3 percent to some 17 billion rupees
(290 million dollars), but imports reached 69 billion rupees(1.2
billion dollars), the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Of the volume, exports to India rose by 40.8 percent at 4.2
billion rupees (70 million dollars), imports from India valued at
19.3 billion rupees (330 million dollars), up 2.5 percent. Whereas
exports to other countries stood at about 12.7 billion rupees (220
million dollars), up 9.9 percent, as against an increase of 37.8
percent in imports at 49.6 billion rupees (870 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
During this nine months, Nepal's trade deficit rose by 29
percent to about 52 billion rupees (912 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Trade deficit with India stood at 15 billion rupees (260
million dollars), down 4.7 percent, whereas the figure with other
countries was 36.9 billion rupees (647 million dollars), up 51
percent, the survey said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
