<HEADLINE> Future of Indo-Pak People Lies in Togetherness: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 20 (Xinhua)-- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral said here today that the future of the people of India and
Pakistan would be in their togetherness and both countries have
been trying to cover the ground which remained uncovered so far.
</P>
<P>
In an interview to 'Home TV' telecast this morning, the prime
minister said that the talks between New Delhi and Islamabad "are
not for the fun of it, nor for avoiding issues, but to lead to
something, to understand each other".
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan resumed their bilateral talks on the foreign
secretary level in March this year and their foreign ministers and
prime ministers also held useful dialogues in April and May.
</P>
<P>
Gujral said in the interview that "let the conversation not
stop. Let talks follow more talks".
</P>
<P>
Referring to Indian government's decision to ease visa
restrictions for Pakistanis visiting India, Gujral said, "When we
relaxed visas we were not doing a favor to anybody. It is a
product of two things: one humanitarian... the other is that the
more people to people contacts there are, the more understanding
there will be."
</P>
<P>
"I am one of those who suffered partition and I came from that
side. The parents of (Pakistan prime minister) Mr. Nawaz Sharif
went from this side," he further said.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan partitioned in 1947 when they became
independent of British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
Language and ethos would help in the process of improving
bilateral relations, the Indian prime minister added.  
</P>
