<HEADLINE> Islam Basic Principle in State Affairs: Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President-elect Mohammad
Khatami stressed Saturday night that Islam is the basic principle
for building the country, the official news agency IRNA reported
here early this morning.
</P>
<P>
In his first message to the nation after elected in May,
Khatami said, "religious identity of the Muslim people of Iran and
the Islamic revolution should be the basis of an identical
national feeling in building the nation."
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who is expected to be sworn in on August 3, made it
clear that "the creation of a well-developed, independent and free
nation would need the effort of every citizen together with
solidarity and national determination".
</P>
<P>
On May 23, Mohammad Khatami won a landslide victory in the 7th
presidential election. But it is believed that there would be
little room for him to play in running the state affairs because
the country's supreme leader is Seyyed Ali Khamenei who succeeded
the late spiritual leader Seyyed Ruhollah Khomeini in June 1989.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, former cultural and Islamic guidance minister, was
sacked by Khamenei in 1992 because he was labeled as "a
liberal-minded minister" and not close enough to the supreme
leader.
</P>
<P>
In his first message, Khatami said that since his election to
presidency on May 23, he has been concentrating on the present
state of affairs of Iran and on how to form his cabinet. He has
been consulting with experts and professionals for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to local observers, more than 2,000 names have been
introduced to him but there are only 22 ministerial posts in the
cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
