<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Navy Foils Plan To Blast Navy Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Navy Saturday foiled a
Tamil rebel plan to destroy Trincomalee Navy Base using limpet
mines, according to military sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted a navy spokesman in Trincomalee Town as
saying the rebel plan, uncovered in the nick of time, was to blow
up at least six navy vessels inside the Trincomalee Harbor, 250
kilometers from Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The rebel plan came to light when a group of navy divers
carrying out a special under-water search operation detected six
powerful sea mines.
</P>
<P>
Each mine weighed approximately 50 kgs. The devises were later
defused, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
All six mines were rigged with necessary equipment to fix them
on to the hull of vessels, said the sources adding that The mines
were discovered at a point close to Clappenburg within the
Trincomalee Navy base.
</P>
<P>
The sources believed that the mines were left behind by a sea
Tiger cadre who was killed last December when the Navy discharged
'depth charger', usually used to prevent sea Tigers approaching
the harbor area.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war for a separate Tamil
state in the north-east of the country since 1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
