Karlos Westendorp pressed the charges in his remarks made to the
Sarajevo-based newspaper Dnevni Avaz published today.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp blasted Serb leaders for noncooperation in launching
a single currency, and the Muslim-Croat Federation for similar
attitude toward the Dayton accord signed in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
The outlawed Croatian Union of Herceg-Bosnia is still
functioning, he noted, adding that its existence will impede
possible agreements among all three parties in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The PIC official attributed the noncooperation to the pursuit
of their own interests by the different ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The Muslims are trying to control the entire Bosnian territory
while the Serbs are attempting to break away from Bosnia and the
Croats are seeking absolute autonomy, Westendorp said. 
</P>
