<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas To Fuel Metropolitan Stoves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- On October 1, a special natural
gas torch will be ignited at Tian'anmen Square, said today's
"China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The torch marks the change which will take place in many
Beijing residents' lives. After October 1, they will cook with
natural gas from Changqing Oil and Natural Gas Field about 900
kilometers northwest of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The change is expected to alleviate Beijing's pollution
significantly since natural gas is much cleaner than coal.
</P>
<P>
Changqing Field is in the Ordos Basin, which includes north
Shaanxi and parts of Gansu, Ningxia, Shanxi and Inner Mongolia. It
covers 370,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Following a series of crucial discoveries in recent years,
Changqing boasts the largest natural gas field in the country. By
1996, the field had 241 billion cubic meters of controlled
reserves, said Hu Wenrui, deputy general manager of Changqing
Petroleum Exploration Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"Only six percent of total estimated gas reserves have been
proven," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hu said the bureau was building a large natural gas development
project with a 3-billion-cubic-meter annual production capacity.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project is expected to provide 1.5
billion cubic meters of gas annually.
</P>
<P>
A large gas collecting, purifying and distributing center in
Jingbian County can handle 10 million cubic meters of gas a day.
</P>
<P>
A 860-km gas pipeline from Jingbian to Beijing was completed in
early July. It is expected to transport 1.1 billion cubic meters
of gas to the capital annually.
</P>
<P>
Another pipeline linking the field and Shaanxi's Xi'an has been
transporting natural gas to Xi'an since July 1. It is capable of
carrying 800 million cubic meters of gas every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
