<HEADLINE> Colombia to Award "Luis Carlos Galan" Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Colombia will award an
international prize on August 18 to individuals, organizations or
communities that have played an outstanding role in strengthening
democracy, peace and human rights.
</P>
<P>
The organizer, the Institute for the Development of Democracy,
said here today in a press release that it has received a total of
76 nominations for the prize named after Luis Carlos Galan, a
liberal leader of Colombia who was assassinated on August 18,
1989, in the Public Plaza of Soacha, a community near Bogota.
</P>
<P>
Among the candidates for the prize, to be delivered for the
first time, were UNESCO General Director Federico Mayor Zaragosa,
South African President Nelson Mandela, Colombian Police General
Director Rosso Jose Serrano Cadena, and the president of the
Kinshasa Association for Democracy, Jean Marie Mulumba Tshimbumba.
</P>
<P>
The members of the jury will be former Ecuadoran President
Rodrigo Borja, former Colombian Foreign Minister Diego Uribe
Vargas, journalist and academician Luis Villar Borda, Director of
the Colombian Association of Universities Galo Burbano, and
Gabriel Galan Sarmiento, the elder brother of Luis Carlos Galan.
</P>
<P>
The prize-winner will get a diploma, a sculpture on the theme
of peace, democracy and human rights, and 100,000 U.S. dollars in
cash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
