<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Inflames Seasonal Goods Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's hottest summer in 50
years is frustrating residents, straining utilities but igniting
seasonal businesses, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Air conditioner producers and sellers possibly profited most as
air conditioner sales swept the city.
</P>
<P>
In many Beijing shops, air conditioners, even samples, are sold.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi and Meidi After-Sales Center said it had to stop
providing air conditioners to small and medium-sized shops to
guarantee supplies for department stores and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
With so many people jostling to buy air conditioners, most
after-sales centers were surprised because they had far from
enough professionals to install them, an industry insider said.
</P>
<P>
Most air conditioner producers have revoked their guarantees to
deliver and install air conditioners within 24 hours and offered a
five- or seven-day guarantee instead, the industry insider said.
</P>
<P>
Sales of electric fans also jumped. They are the best choice
for people who cannot afford air conditioners or who use electric
fans instead of air conditioners when the weather is not
unbearably hot.
</P>
<P>
Electric fans at Beijing's Shuang'an Market are sold out, and
Guiyou Shopping Center reported daily sales volume of 200 electric
fans.
</P>
<P>
Straw and bamboo sleeping mats are selling better than last
year when it rained more frequently and the temperature was lower,
street vendors said.
</P>
<P>
While the heat fuels sales in the city, it is withering profits
for farmers. In the mountainous areas outside Beijing, farmers are
hurriedly trying to save 20,000 hectares of corn.
</P>
<P>
The sweltering heat has put power and water companies under
great stress.
</P>
<P>
Daily electricity use was 4.71 million kilowatt-hours, a July
record, said Ji Hong of the Beijing Power Corp. The company is in
charge of the city's electricity supply.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 800,000 kilowatt-hours more than last year's July
record, Ji said.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Tap Water Co. said it might have to cut the water
pressure if demand continues to rise. The company is providing
water at full capacity: 2.4 million cubic meters, company
spokesperson Yao Lei said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Commercial Banks Upgrade Auditing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- China's four State banks severed
from the central government adminstration have been tightening
bank audition and surveillance in the process of transforming to
commercial banks, the China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"(The four Banks) have never been so concerned about the
quality of their capital," the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The banks are the Agricultural Bank of China (ABC), the
Bank of China (BOC), the Commercial and Industrial Bank of China
(CIBC) and the China Construction Bank.
</P>
<P>
"It is something the sound operation of the bank and our
reputation depends on," ABC president Shi Jiliang said.
</P>
<P>
The ABC, the most burdened of the country's top four banks, is
taking a lead in finding an effective way to secure the bank's
healthy performance. Early in June, it set a committee responsible
for auditing and supervision.
</P>
<P>
A BOC official said his bank set up an auditing group headed by
the bank chief in 1995. And the group's main task this year is to
check the unaccounted funds and curb illegal use of capital, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yang Kaisheng, vice-president of the CIBC, said the bank had
unified control over the credit capital. The bank keeps detailed
records of each client to make sure that credit is used
effectively.
</P>
<P>
And the Construction Bank has established a risk-monitoring
system that warns of risks in advance, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Before 1994, all the four State banks acted as arms specialized
in performing the central government policies, when all the credit
was granted under the mandate of the central government, and
whether the credit could be repaid was not important to the banks'
operation.
</P>
<P>
As a result of too many branches and employees, the head
offices were simply unable to exercise their authority in managing
their entire network.
</P>
<P>
The newly established supervisory mechanism is expected to
ensure the sound and healthy growth of the four commercial banks,
the Daily said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
