<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Decline Normal: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The latest drop in foreign
investment in China is nothing to fuss about, but a normal outcome
of China's economic progress and will not affect their long-term
interest in the country, the China daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Although statistics are alleged to suggest foreign investors'
interest in China is waning, Zhang Shangtang, vice-chairman of the
China Association of Enterprises with Foreign Investment,
downplayed those rumors.
</P>
<P>
"It really should be seen as a normal thing, regarding the
decline in the growth rate of contractual foreign funds in recent
months," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation show contractual foreign investment was 23.3 billion
US dollars in the first half of the year, down 48.76 percent from
the same period last year. But direct investment surged 5.49
percent to 20.7 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
A researcher from the State Planning Commission said the
abnormal growth of foreign investment in the first half of last
year led to this year's decrease.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors jostled to clinch deals before April 1, 1996,
when the import tariff exemption on capital goods expired, thus
causing contracted investment to skyrocket in the first several
months of last year.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan, chairman of US-based Westinghouse, told the
China Daily that although China's policy adjustment affect foreign
investment, thoughtful foreign investors would keep a long-term
perspective toward their business in China.
</P>
<P>
It is not justifiable for China to always run on the fast
track after being the world's second largest investment target for
four consecutive years, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
However, a good sign surfaced that investment quality is
improving, according to Zhang Shangtang.
</P>
<P>
China approved 9,763 foreign-funded enterprises in the past six
months, down 30.5 percent from last year. But per-project
investment hit 2.12 million US dollars, higher than 1.7 million US
dollars in 1996 and one million US dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Small foreign-funded plants seeking short-term returns are
moving to neighboring countries because of rising costs,
industrial adjustment and surging dumping allegations, Zhang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
