<HEADLINE> HK Return to Help Chinese Oil Producer: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The return of Hong Kong is an
opportunity for the China National Offshore Oil Corp (CNOOC) to
develop, CNOOC President Wang Yan said.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC is the monopoly authorized by the State Council to be
engaged in the exploration for, development, production,
utilization and marketing of offshore oil and gas resources.
</P>
<P>
It is considering many measure to raise funds to develop
downstream products and expand overseas, the China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, an international financial center, will be crucial
in helping CNOOC attain its goal, Wang was quoted by the Daily as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC created an investment company in Hong Kong to raise
funds, which is expected to be listed in local securities markets.
</P>
<P>
The company has benefited from Hong Kong since its founding in
1982, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The China Ocean Oil Fields Services (Hong Kong) Ltd, a
subsidiary of the CNOOC set up in 1982, has recruited a lot of
overseas technical experts.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC has accommodated 8,600 overseas experts in the past
14 years, mostly through Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Wang also disclosed that his company is prepared to cooperate
with Hong Kong's Merchant Bureau Group Ltd. and other partners to
build the Nanhai Petrochemical project in Guangdong Province. The
first phase of the project is capable of producing 800,000 tons of
ethylene annually.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC is expected to pump 16 million tons of oil and 8.5
million to 10 billion cubic meters of natural gas annually by
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
