<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970720.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Gap To Continue Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- China's trade surplus continued to
swell this year, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
But experts say the gap will have some negative effects on
long-term development.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade surplus, buoyed by rocketing exports and
declining imports since the start of the year, hit 17.8 billion US
dollars in June. The 1996 surplus was 12.2 billion dollars; the
1995 surplus was 16.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Li Jian, a researcher with the International Trade Research
Institute, said the surplus was a result of the country's
macro-economic control.
</P>
<P>
A direct consequence of the tight credit policy is the
slackened domestic purchasing power. Although Chinese savings are
increasing, commercial and industrial sectors complained domestic
spending was sluggish. As a result, the demand for imported
products is waning.
</P>
<P>
Another outcome is the ebbing investment demand reflected by
contractual foreign investment, which plunged 48.7 percent in the
first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The declining investment is a more direct result of China's
elimination of the tax exemption on capital goods imports since
last April. It caused plant equipment imports to fall. They
usually account for about 20 percent of China's imports.
</P>
<P>
Li said the continuous surplus could buoy China's foreign
exchange reserve and lead to an inequilibrium of China's
international payment balance.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Baoliang, a researcher for the State Information Center,
said that the trade surplus would ultimately lead to a rise in the
value of renminbi, which in turn, will raise costs and hurt
exports.
</P>
<P>
China's exports will continue to rise although slowly,
throughout the year. Therefore, the surplus will become even
larger this year as the import situation will not change
considerably, Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
