<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine, World Bank Plan Loan to Boost Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and the World Bank (WB) are
preparing a new crediting program to develop the country's
business, said a World Bank official.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Drume, head of the WB mission here, said the program
would focus on four areas: privatization, the stock market,
accountancy and bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
The program will come before the WB Board of Executive
Directors for approval in November, at which time the actual size
of the loan and the conditions of its disbursement will be
finalized.
</P>
<P>
However, present requirement for the disbursement of the WB
credit will include the privatization of 9,500 enterprises, with
at least 70 percent of their stock being sold by June 30, 1998, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The bank also wants the number of companies excluded from
privatization to be cut. At present, this number stands at
4,000. In addition, the State Property Fund is to prepare
individual privatization plans for 10 major companies before
September 30.
</P>
<P>
The WB has disbursed two batches of an earlier business
development loan, the 310 million dollars of Enterprise
Development Adjustment Loan (EDAL). The three-batch EDAL loan is
to be repaid over a 17 year period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
