<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philips Unloads Its Grundig Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Philips Electronics NV said
Friday that it had sold most of its one-third stake in Grundig AG,
further distancing itself from the struggling German television
and audio equipment manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
Philips, Europe's biggest maker of consumer electronics,
slashed its 31.6 percent stake to just five percent, selling the
rest to Botts &AMP; Co., a private London investment bank. The price
will be determined by the "future value" of the shares, Philips
said.
</P>
<P>
Philips surrendered control of Grundig in January. The company
had cost Philips 955 million U.S. dollars since 1984. Philips is
also disputing the 671 million Deutsche marks (374.9 million
dollars) in 1996 losses reported by Grundig.
</P>
<P>
It said the stated loss had been inflated by extensive
provisions for new policies adopted after the year-end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
